<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-159-236 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 738 059</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  May 6 1991 n640 p1(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Do patent laws need reforms? (Texas Instruments vs. Gilbert Hyattdebate over single-chip microcomputer rights raises debate)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bellinger, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Texas Instruments Inc versus Gilbert Hyatt debate over thepatent rights to the single-chip microcomputer is raisingquestions over the need for patent law reforms.andP;  Current problemsinclude the amount of time and tremendous financial costs involvedin prosecuting, the secrecy that surrounds the system, and thepitting of large corporations against individuals.andP;  Controversycenters on the US 'first to invent' patent system; most of therest of the world utilizes a 'first to file' procedure.andP;  Thiscauses a problem with international patent rights.andP;  The US isproposing an option of either system.andP;  The US has one of theworld's only patent systems that requires secrecy until the patentis granted; most countries publish patent applications within 18months.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Texas Instruments Inc. (Patents).andO;Ticker:    TXN.andO;Topic:     PatentLegal IssuesInternational LawRightsAnalysisCase StudyIntellectual Property.andO;Person:    Hyatt, Gilbert (Patents).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>